postcontent:
LSB#: 111202KF02

Make: Colt

Model: Single Action Army – Black Powder Frame

Serial Number: 90581

Year of Manufacture: 1883

Caliber: .45 Colt

Action Type: Single Action Revolver

Markings: The gun has almost full coverage engraving, with few markings remaining. The rear face of the cylinder is marked with a “P”. The frame and trigger guard are marked “90581”, as is the backstrap. This number on backstrap looks to have been stuck over. The loading gate is numbered “1644”. The inside of the grip panels are marked “26 Colt Frontier / Single Action Army”.

Barrel Length: Measures 4.707”

Sights / Optics: The gun is mounted with standard Single Action Army sights.

Stock Configuration & Condition: The grips are aftermarket imitation mother of pearl. These grips are sound, showing no cracks or losses and fit a bit large to the grip frame. The grips rate in about Excellent overall condition.

Type of Finish: Hard Chrome

Finish Originality: Refinished, Applied After Engraving

Bore Condition: The bore is a bit rough and dark and the rifling is visible the entire length, but worn. There is erosion in the bore, but the bore is shootable.

Overall Condition: This gun retains about 95% of its re-applied metal finish. The modern finish shows almost no wear. There is very little visible pitting under the finish on the exposed surfaces, as metal preparation is good. There is pitting visible on the metal under the grips, inside the loading gate and at other internal areas where finish was applied but the area would not be seen externally. The engraving is loose, but deep and helps dress this old pistol up a bit. The Screw heads are worn but serviceable. The markings are clear where present, and some possibly re-struck. Overall, this gun rates in about Very Good condition.

Mechanics: The action does not function 100% correctly. The hammer does come back and the cylinder advances but the hammer does not "lock" at full cock. Pulling the trigger does drop the hammer. Its almost as if the hammer was rebounding about 1/4". The trigger is pushed all of the way to the front of its slot with a strong spring. Perhaps this gun was reassembled incorrectly. Black Powder please, to be safe…

title: For Sale:  H&K 416 A1
postcontent:
This is a H&K MMR 556 A1 with the original box and Mag[img]

THE MR556A1
A direct descendent of the HK416, the MR556A1 is a semi-automatic rifle developed by Heckler & Koch as a premium level commercial/civilian firearm with match rifle capability. Like the HK416, the MR556A1 is a major product improvement over conventional AR-type carbines and rifles.

The MR556A1 uses the HK proprietary gas piston operating system, employing a piston and a solid operating “pusher” rod in place of the gas tube normally found in AR15/M16/M4-style firearms.

This method of operation virtually eliminates malfunctions that are common to direct impingement gas systems since hot carbon fouling and waste gases do not enter the receiver area. This is the same key feature critical to the success of the HK416 rifles used by leading military and law enforcement customers.

The MR556A1 is manufactured in the USA using American and German made components. The MR556A1 uses many of the same assemblies and accessories originally developed for the HK416 including the HK free-floating four-quadrant rail system.

The HK Free Floating Rail System (FFRS) handguard has four MIL-STD-1913 “Picatinny” rails and allows all current accessories, sights, lights, and aimers used on M4/M16-type arms to be fitted to the MR Series. The HK rail system can be installed and removed with simple tools and returns to zero when reinstalled.

The MR556A1 also has a Picantinny rail machined into the top of its upper receiver for mounting optics and mechanical sights. Unlike earlier prototypes, major subassemblies, including the MR556A1 upper receiver/barrel assembly, are fully interchangeable with other high quality AR-style firearms. MR556A1 upper receiver kits can be used to retrofit competing legacy AR systems.

Like the famous HK416, the MR556A1 uses a German-made barrel produced by Heckler & Koch’s famous cold hammer forging process. The highest quality steel is used in this unique manufacturing process producing a barrel that provides superior accuracy and long service life.

But unlike the HK416, the MR556A1 does not use a chrome-lined barrel. Chrome-lining can sometimes mask bore imperfections and negatively affect accuracy. For the new series of Heckler & Koch semi-automatic MR rifles, HK designers and engineers believe best accuracy comes with an unlined bore.

Used with the HK Free Floating Rail System, the barrel does not touch the handguard, ensuring the barrel is truly free-floating for maximum accuracy.

The unchromed barrel has an internal profile of 6 lands and grooves with a 1 in 7 inch (178 mm) twist. It is also moderately “swagged” with a slightly smaller internal diameter at the muzzle end than the chamber end. This feature has a positive effect on bullet accuracy and velocity. The thick, heavy contour 16.5-inch MR556A1 barrel also contributes to its excellent accuracy.

A precise enhanced two-stage trigger adds significantly to the accuracy of the MR556A1 and an extended latch charging handle makes operating the rifle with a telescopic sight easier. The retractable buttstock can be locked into a solid, non-moving position by tightening an Allen screw in the bottom of the stock. Special target rifle takedown pins ensure the upper and lower receivers are firmly mated for accurate performance.

Designed to function with a wide variety of high quality 5.56 x 45 mm ammunition, the MR556A1 uses a C.I.P. dimensioned chamber (a chamber with dimensions specified by the Commission Internationale Permanente).The MR556A1 also functions reliably with most quality Caliber .223 Remington ammunition.

The MR556A1 is being produced with the same commitment to quality as German-made HK firearms. By using joint U.S./German manufacturing, Heckler & Koch leverages the relative strengths of two continents to make the preeminent AR-type firearm, combining the designs innovations of the USA and Germany into one new product.

The MR556A1 rifle is now available. Suggested Retail is $3,295 (includes rifle, HK 30-round steel magazine, set of HK diopter sights, HK multi-tool, lock, and case). An accessory MR556A1 Upper Receiver Kit will be available at a later date.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Original Weatherby Vanguard,  Deluxe, 30.06 never fired!!
postcontent:
WEATHERBY VANGUARD, Circa 1973-1974, CAL 30-06, NO FRONT SIGHT (appraised 1993 @$750), discontinued and reintroduced as Deluxe.  (The serial number is prefixed with the single letter 'V', Later deluxe models were prefixed with 'VGD and VGX', all subsequent vanguard models were prefixed with 2 - 3 letters.)  Weatherby bolt sleeve recall mod applied 10/2011 Weatherby bolt sleeve recall mod applied 10/2011.  

There is a fine scatch in the stock about a third of the way down that came from moving in and out of the safe, does not appear to have broken clear coat.  And a slight rub mark, again from handling in the safe near the right side forearm that's barely noticeable and the camera won't pick it up.  Those are the only issues with this rifle.

The original Weatherby Vanguard and the subsequent VGD and VGX Deluxe models looked almost identical to the Mark V Deluxe rifle, and sported a very similar walnut stock, right down to the checkering, forearm tips, grip caps, line spacers, and recoil pads. The stock finish was high gloss and the metal finish was the renowned Weatherby high luster blue. These deluxe models were discontinued in the early 1990s.  The finish on the receiver housing of this particular rifle is plum which was not uncommon in the early models.

Local, FTF, Cash sale to eligible AL residents is preferred.  Sale to non-AL residents will be FFL to FFL with the buyer paying for shipping.

postcontent:
I am not interested in selling..... but just looking to see what anyone might be intersted in trading.

This is a Para Warthog with a custom Cerakote Flat Tan Dark Earth coating, with black controls.  This is a sweet little 1911, that is easy to carry concealed and fun to shoot.  The biggest complaint about this gun is a FTF (failure to feed) issue that is addressed with new mag springs.  I have two mags for this with aftermarket Wolff Springs installed and I have never had any issue at all.  I am looking to trade for something of similar value.  I have had this for a few years, and looking to try something new.  Maybe 100 rounds through this pistol. 

Comes with original box, papers, two mags, and leather holster. Retail for around $800.00.  

From Para:  The PARA Warthog is the world's smallest .45 ACP, 10+1 round, semi-automatic pistol. It is unbelievably powerful for its compact size... only 6.75 inches in length and 4.5 inches high including the magazine. The genius of PARA is the reliability needed in a 3-inch 1911 style pistol, from its unique dual recoil spring system to its cone barrel lockup. The Power Extractor was designed for flawless feeding and extraction with the fast cycling time of the Warthog's compact slide. The Warthog's match grade ramped barrel delivers incredible accuracy in a micro compact pistol. The frames have integral plunger tubes and grip screw bushings and ultra thin polymer grips.
